        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2632</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.3.2</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> be a complex endowed with a biregular filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>.
    The following conditions are equivalent:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        The spectral sequence defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> degenerates (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1=E_\infty ]]></fr:tex>).
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        The morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d\colon  K^i\to  K^{i+1}]]></fr:tex> are strictly compatible with the filtrations.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>866</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#306</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-306.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We will prove this in the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> is a category of modules.
      For fixed <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, the hypothesis that the arrows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> with domains <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex> be zero for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\geqslant 1]]></fr:tex> implies that, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  F^p(K^{p+q})]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[dx\in  F^{p+1}(K^{p+q+1})]]></fr:tex>, then there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  K^{p+q}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[dy=0]]></fr:tex> and such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> have the same image in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1^{pq}]]></fr:tex>.
      Modifying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> by a boundary, and setting <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x-y]]></fr:tex>, we then have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \forall  x\in  F^p(K^{p+q})         \left [           dx\in  F^{p+1}(K^{p+q+1})           \implies  \exists  z\text { s.t. } z\in  F^{p+1}(K^{p+q}) \text { and } dz=dx         \right ]       ]]></fr:tex>
      or, in other words,
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         F^{p+1}(K^{p+q+1}) \cap  dF^p(K^{p+q})         = dF^{p+1}(K^{p+q}).       \tag{1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>

    <fr:p>If this condition is satisfied for arbitrary <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, then by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> we have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         F^{p+r} \cap  dF^p         = dF^{p+r}       ]]></fr:tex>
      which, for large <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+r]]></fr:tex>, can be written as
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         F^p \cap  dK         = dF^p.       \tag{2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>

    <fr:p>Claim (2) trivially implies (1), and is equivalent to (ii), which proves the proposition.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
